{"subject_name":"Math Basic","chapters":[{"chapter_name":"Graph","topics":[{"topic_name":"all topic list","topic_html":"<div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto px-2 pb-5 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\">Here are 20 topics about mathematical graphs that can help in understanding different types of graphs and their applications:<br><br>1. **Introduction to Cartesian Coordinates**: Understanding the X-Y plane, axes, and the concept of coordinates.<br><br>2. **Plotting Points**: How to plot points (x, y) on a Cartesian plane and interpret their positions.<br><br>3. **Linear Equations and Graphs**: Understanding the graph of a linear equation, slope, and intercepts.<br><br>4. **Quadratic Equations and Parabolas**: Exploring the graph of quadratic functions and the properties of parabolas.<br><br>5. **Exponential Functions and Their Graphs**: Analyzing the shape and characteristics of exponential function graphs.<br><br>6. **Understanding Slope**: The concept of slope, its calculation, and its significance in determining the steepness of a line.<br><br>7. **Intercepts and Their Importance**: Detailed study of X-intercepts and Y-intercepts and their relevance in graphs.<br><br>8. **Graphing Inequalities**: How to represent inequalities on a graph and shade the appropriate regions.<br><br>9. **Understanding Asymptotes**: Analyzing the behavior of graphs near asymptotes, especially in rational functions.<br><br>10. **Piecewise Functions and Their Graphs**: Understanding and graphing piecewise functions, which have different expressions over different intervals.<br><br>11. **Graph Transformations**: Studying how graphs change with shifts, reflections, stretches, and compressions.<br><br>12. **Logarithmic Functions and Their Graphs**: Exploring the graph of logarithmic functions and their properties.<br><br>13. **Polynomials and Their Graphs**: Understanding the shapes and key features of polynomial function graphs.<br><br>14. **Trigonometric Graphs**: Analyzing the graphs of sine, cosine, tangent, and other trigonometric functions.<br><br>15. **Cubic and Higher-Order Polynomials**: Examining the characteristics of cubic functions and higher-order polynomials on a graph.<br><br>16. **Rational Functions and Their Graphs**: Studying the graphs of rational functions, including identifying vertical and horizontal asymptotes.<br><br>17. **Parametric Equations and Graphing**: Understanding how to graph parametric equations and interpret their meaning.<br><br>18. **Polar Coordinates and Graphing**: Exploring the concept of polar coordinates and graphing in the polar plane.<br><br>19. **Vector Functions and Space Curves**: Graphing vector functions and understanding the representation of curves in space.<br><br>20. **Understanding Graph Symmetry**: Studying the symmetry of graphs with respect to axes, origin, and lines, and its implications on the function.<br><br>These topics cover a wide range of mathematical graphs and provide a strong foundation for understanding various types of graphs in mathematics.</div>","topic_id":26},{"topic_name":"Cartesian Coordinate System","topic_html":"<div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto px-2 pb-5 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h3 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"heading\">Cartesian Coordinate System</h3><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">The Cartesian coordinate system is a mathematical framework used to describe the location of points in space. Named after the French mathematician <span style=\"\" class=\"mx-1\"><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;source=web&amp;rct=j&amp;opi=89978449&amp;url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%25C3%25A9_Descartes&amp;ved=2ahUKEwj06PPgy_SHAxUnzTgGHQrPM3EQFnoECD4QAQ&amp;usg=AOvVaw00IBVfVUe0b77PSuVgP0pI\">Ren√© Descartes</a></span>, this system is fundamental in both geometry and algebra.</p><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Introduction to the X-Y Plane</h5><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">The X-Y plane, also known as the Cartesian plane, is a two-dimensional surface defined by two perpendicular number lines:</p><div class=\"d-flex flex-column p-2 gap-1 my-2 mx-auto rounded-1 media-container\" data-el=\"media-container\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/media/image___3836Basic 2d graph(1).png\" class=\"\"></div><ul class=\"ul ps-3 ms-2 ps-md-4 py-3 li-disk\" data-el=\"list-container\"> <li data-el=\"list\" class=\"\"><strong class=\"\"><span style=\"color: #ff0080;\" class=\"\">X-Axis</span> (Horizontal Axis)</strong>: Represents the horizontal component of a point's location.</li> <li data-el=\"list\" class=\"\"><strong class=\"\"><span style=\"color: #8080ff;\" class=\"\">Y-Axis</span> (Vertical Axis)</strong>: Represents the vertical component of a point's location.</li> <li data-el=\"list\" class=\"\">The point where the X-axis and Y-axis intersect is called the <strong class=\"\"><span style=\"color: #8000ff;\" class=\"\">origin</span> (o)</strong>. The origin has coordinates (0,0)</li></ul></div><div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto p-2 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Plotting Points Using Coordinates (x, y)</h5><ul class=\"ul li-disk ps-4 ps-md-5 py-3\" data-el=\"list-container\"><li data-el=\"list\" class=\"\">x is the distance from the point to the <span style=\"color: #8080ff;\" class=\"\">Y-axis</span> (measured along the <span style=\"color: #ff0080;\" class=\"\">X-axis</span>)</li><li data-el=\"list\" class=\"\">\ny is the distance from the point to the <span style=\"color: #ff0080;\" class=\"\">X-axis</span> (measured along the <span style=\"color: #8080ff;\" class=\"\">Y-axis</span>)\n</li></ul></div><div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto p-2 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Example of (3,2) point :<br></h5><div class=\"d-flex flex-column p-2 gap-1 my-2 mx-auto rounded-1 media-container\" data-el=\"media-container\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/media/image___60043,2 point 2d graph(1).png\"></div></div><div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto p-2 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Example of (-3,2) point :<br></h5><div class=\"d-flex flex-column p-2 gap-1 my-2 mx-auto rounded-1 media-container\" data-el=\"media-container\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/media/image___3023n3,2 point 2d graph.png\" class=\"\"></div></div><div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto p-2 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Example of (3,-2) point :<br></h5><div class=\"d-flex flex-column p-2 gap-1 my-2 mx-auto rounded-1 media-container\" data-el=\"media-container\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/media/image___8443,n2 point 2d graph.png\"></div></div><div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto p-2 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Example of (-3,-2) point :<br></h5><div class=\"d-flex flex-column p-2 gap-1 my-2 mx-auto rounded-1 media-container\" data-el=\"media-container\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/media/image___2541n3,n2 point 2d graph.png\"></div></div><div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto px-2 pb-5 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Graph Basic Concept :<br></h5><ul class=\"ul li-disk ps-4 ps-md-5 py-3\" data-el=\"list-container\"><li data-el=\"list\">Graphs provide a visual way to represent data, making it easier to understand relationships between variables</li><li data-el=\"list\" class=\"\">The <span style=\"color: #ff0080;\" class=\"\">X-axis</span> typically represents the <span style=\"\" class=\"hl hl-default\">independent</span> variable, or the variable that changes in response to some input or condition</li><li data-el=\"list\" class=\"\">The<span style=\"color: #8080ff;\" class=\"\"> Y-axis</span> usually represents the <span style=\"\" class=\"hl hl-default\">dependent </span>variable, which changes as a result of the variations in the <span style=\"color: #ff0080;\" class=\"\">X-axis</span></li><li data-el=\"list\" class=\"\">The main data in a graph is the height in <span style=\"color: #8080ff;\" class=\"\">y axis</span></li><li data-el=\"list\">The height or value of Y at any point on the graph shows the magnitude of the dependent variable for a specific value of X</li><li data-el=\"list\">The slope of a line on a graph represents the rate of change of the dependent variable with respect to the independent variable</li></ul></div>","topic_id":27},{"topic_name":"Basic Math Graph","topic_html":"<div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto px-2 pb-5 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h3 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"heading\">Creating Graph with Real world Example<br></h3></div>\n<div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto px-2 pb-5 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Example 1 : Babies weight from age 1 - 5<br></h5><div class=\"col-12\">\n                \n                </div><div class=\"col-12\">\n                <div class=\"scroll py-3 scroll-both scroll-min scroll-on-hover\" data-el=\"table-container\">\n                <table class=\"table mx-auto table-striped\" data-el=\"table\"><thead class=\"table-border\"><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"\">age (year)<br></th><th scope=\"col\">1<br></th><th scope=\"col\">2<br></th><th scope=\"col\">3<br></th><th scope=\"col\">4<br></th><th scope=\"col\">5<br></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><th scope=\"row\" class=\"\">weight (kg)<br></th><td>9<br></td><td>11<br></td><td>13<br></td><td>15</td><td>18<br></td></tr></tbody></table>        \n                </div>\n                </div><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">so when age is&nbsp; 1 year any nomal baby's weight is 9kg,in 3 year the weight will be 13kg<br></p><div class=\"d-flex flex-column p-2 gap-1 my-2 mx-auto rounded-1 media-container\" data-el=\"media-container\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/media/image___2536Practise child graph.png\" class=\"\"></div><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">in this graph every one unit of y-axis count as 2<br></p><h5 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"title\">Graph with Bar<br></h5><div class=\"d-flex flex-column p-2 gap-1 my-2 mx-auto rounded-1 media-container\" data-el=\"media-container\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/media/image___3291Practise child bar graph.png\"></div></div>","topic_id":28},{"topic_name":"Slope","topic_html":"<div class=\"col-12 col-md-11 col-lg-9 my-2 mx-auto px-2 pb-5 border content-section rounded-2\" data-el=\"section\"><h3 class=\"p-2 mb-2\" data-el=\"heading\">Slope<br></h3><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">The main thing in a 2d graph is the height or the value of y cordinate for each unit in x .The changes on x-axis is fixed as it moved from left to right and step is&nbsp; defined.But the value of y is not fixed it is dynamic.<br></p><div class=\"d-flex flex-column p-2 gap-1 my-2 mx-auto border rounded-1 media-container\" data-el=\"media-container\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/media/image___9894saved.png\"></div><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">In this graph there are many different height for each value in x-axis.The height refer the output for each input on x-axis.So where is the slope&nbsp; here ?<br></p><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">Before finding the value of slove we have understand what its value refer.The Value of slope refer the changes of height in the measurement of y-unit for each step moving in x-axis.We need at least two point to the find slope between them.<br></p><p class=\"light-note p-3 rounded-1 mx-2 mb-2 text-light box-bg\">How many units  does the line go up or down for each unit it goes across .The result of slope refer only one step&nbsp; it moving toward +x&nbsp; direction<br></p><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">Now look at points B(1,2) and C(2,4). What is the slope of the line connecting B and C? Alternatively, we can ask: By how many units does the height increase or decrease as you move from point B to point C?</p><div class=\"math-box p-3 border rounded-2 box-bg my-2\"><mjx-container class=\"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attached_0\" jax=\"CHTML\" style=\"font-size: 124%; position: relative;\" tabindex=\"0\" ctxtmenu_counter=\"0\"><mjx-math class=\"MJX-TEX\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><mjx-mstyle><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D460 TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D459 TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D45C TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D45D TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D452 TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mo class=\"mjx-n\" space=\"4\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c3D\"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-mfrac space=\"4\"><mjx-frac type=\"d\"><mjx-num><mjx-nstrut type=\"d\"></mjx-nstrut><mjx-mrow><mjx-msub><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D466 TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-script style=\"vertical-align: -0.15em;\"><mjx-mn class=\"mjx-n\" size=\"s\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c32\"></mjx-c></mjx-mn></mjx-script></mjx-msub><mjx-mo class=\"mjx-n\" space=\"3\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c2212\"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-msub space=\"3\"><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D466 TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-script style=\"vertical-align: -0.15em;\"><mjx-mn class=\"mjx-n\" size=\"s\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c31\"></mjx-c></mjx-mn></mjx-script></mjx-msub></mjx-mrow></mjx-num><mjx-dbox><mjx-dta