 TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D459 TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D45C TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D45D TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mi class=\"mjx-i\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c1D452 TEX-I\"></mjx-c></mjx-mi><mjx-mo class=\"mjx-n\" space=\"4\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c3D\"></mjx-c></mjx-mo><mjx-mn class=\"mjx-n\" space=\"4\"><mjx-c class=\"mjx-c32\"></mjx-c></mjx-mn></mjx-mstyle></mjx-math><mjx-assistive-mml unselectable=\"on\" display=\"inline\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>s</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mstyle></math></mjx-assistive-mml></mjx-container><br></div><p class=\"p p-2 px-3 mb-2\" data-el=\"text\">So the slope of AC is 2. This doesn't mean that the height increases by 2 units as you move from A to C. That would be incorrect, as the height actually increases by 4 units from A to C. Instead, the slope of 2 indicates that for every 1 unit you move horizontally from point A toward point C, the height increases by 2 units.</p><p class=\"light-note p-3 rounded-1 mx-2 mb-2 text-light box-bg\">\"So the final statement is that the slope refers to the change in height for each unit of horizontal movement from point 1 to point 2, not the total change from point 1 to point 2.\"<br></p></div>","topic_id":29}],"chapter_id":37}]}